{
  "A cold front forms when:": "",
  "A cold air mass pushes under and lifts a warm air mass": "",
  "Pressure rises quickly": "",
  "Warm air advances over cold air": "",
  "Two air masses stop moving": "",
  "A cold front occurs when a cold, dense air mass advances and wedges under a warmer air mass, forcing it to rise rapidly, often producing intense but brief precipitation.": "",
  "Tornadoes are most associated with:": "",
  "Warm fronts": "",
  "Supercell thunderstorms with strong wind shear": "",
  "Stationary fronts": "",
  "High-pressure systems": "",
  "Tornadoes typically form in supercell thunderstorms where strong wind shear creates a rotating updraft (mesocyclone), which can produce a funnel reaching the ground.": "",
  "Hurricanes form over:": "",
  "Flat continental land masses heated by intense tropical sunlight": "",
  "Cold polar ocean waters with temperatures below 10 degrees Celsius": "",
  "High-altitude mountain ranges that force air upward past 3,000 meters": "",
  "Warm tropical ocean water (at least 26.5 degrees C)": "",
  "Hurricanes require warm ocean water of at least 26.5 degrees C to fuel evaporation and provide the energy that drives their powerful winds and heavy rainfall.": "",
  "A warm front produces:": "",
  "Brief but intense thunderstorms concentrated along a narrow band": "",
  "Clear skies and steadily rising temperatures across the whole region": "",
  "Prolonged, steady precipitation over a wide area": "",
  "Only dense fog banks forming along coastal and low-lying valley areas": "",
  "A warm front moves slowly as warm air slides over cold air ahead, producing a wide band of clouds and gentle, steady precipitation that can last for hours.": "",
  "The calm center of a hurricane is called the:": "",
  "Vortex": "",
  "Core": "",
  "Eye": "",
  "Funnel": "",
  "The eye is a roughly circular area of calm, clear skies at the center of a hurricane, typically 30-65 km in diameter, surrounded by the most violent winds in the eyewall.": "",
  "An occluded front forms when:": "",
  "A warm front and cold front diverge from each other, leaving a broad region of stable dry air between them": "",
  "A tropical cyclone moves inland and disrupts pre-existing frontal boundaries across the continental interior": "",
  "Atmospheric pressure stabilizes uniformly across a large region, causing all active frontal boundaries to dissolve": "",
  "A fast-moving cold front overtakes a warm front, lifting the warm air entirely off the ground": "",
  "An occluded front forms in the late stage of a mid-latitude cyclone when a faster cold front catches up to and merges with a warm front, lifting warm air completely off the surface.": "",
  "Thunderstorms require three ingredients:": "",
  "Snow, ice, and wind": "",
  "Moisture, an unstable atmosphere, and a lifting mechanism": "",
  "Only warm air": "",
  "Cold air, dry air, and sunlight": "",
  "Thunderstorms need sufficient moisture for cloud formation, an unstable atmosphere where warm air can rise freely, and a trigger like a front or heating to initiate the upward motion.": "",
  "The Saffir-Simpson scale measures:": "",
  "Hurricane intensity based on sustained wind speed": "",
  "Earthquake intensity": "",
  "Blizzard severity": "",
  "Tornado strength": "",
  "The Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale categorizes hurricanes from Category 1 (119-153 km/h) to Category 5 (over 252 km/h) based on sustained wind speed.": "",
  "A stationary front can cause:": "",
  "Rapid temperature changes": "",
  "Instant clear skies": "",
  "Days of cloudy weather and prolonged precipitation": "",
  "Only light winds": "",
  "A stationary front stalls when neither air mass is strong enough to advance, resulting in extended periods of cloudiness and precipitation along the boundary.": "",
  "The most dangerous part of a hurricane is the:": "",
  "Outer rain bands that extend hundreds of kilometers outward from the center": "",
  "Eyewall, where the strongest winds and heaviest rain occur": "",
  "Central eye where rapidly descending air creates dangerous turbulent gusts": "",
  "Trailing back side of the storm where residual winds briefly intensify": "",
  "The eyewall is the ring of towering cumulonimbus clouds surrounding the eye, containing the most intense winds, heaviest rainfall, and greatest potential for destruction.": "",
  "What is a weather front?": "",
  "The calm area before a storm": "",
  "A line of thunderstorms along a coastline": "",
  "The leading edge of a hurricane": "",
  "The boundary between two air masses of different temperature and humidity characteristics": "",
  "A weather front is the boundary zone where two air masses with different properties (temperature, humidity, density) meet, often producing clouds and precipitation.": "",
  "What is a tornado?": "",
  "A strong wind associated with cold fronts": "",
  "A violently rotating column of air extending from a cumulonimbus cloud to the ground": "",
  "A large-scale tropical storm system": "",
  "A waterspout that moves onto land": "",
  "A tornado is a violently rotating funnel of air that extends from a thunderstorm cloud to the ground, capable of producing winds exceeding 480 km/h in extreme cases.": "",
  "What is storm surge?": "",
  "A large ocean wave caused by an earthquake": "",
  "An abnormal rise in sea level caused by a hurricane's winds and low pressure pushing ocean water ashore": "",
  "A sudden increase in wind speed during a thunderstorm": "",
  "Heavy rainfall from a tropical storm": "",
  "Storm surge is a dome of water pushed ashore by hurricane winds and low pressure, often the most deadly hazard of hurricanes, capable of flooding coastal areas with several meters of water.": "",
  "What does 'Enhanced Fujita scale' mean?": "",
  "A scale that rates tornado intensity from EF0 to EF5 based on damage indicators and estimated wind speeds": "",
  "A scale that measures hurricane wind speed": "",
  "A scale that rates blizzard severity": "",
  "A scale that measures earthquake magnitude": "",
  "The Enhanced Fujita (EF) scale rates tornado intensity from EF0 (light damage, 105-137 km/h) to EF5 (incredible destruction, over 322 km/h) by evaluating damage to structures.": "",
  "What is an air mass?": "",
  "A large body of air with relatively uniform temperature and humidity characteristics that forms over a source region": "",
  "A column of air directly above a specific location": "",
  "The total amount of air in the atmosphere": "",
  "A fast-moving stream of air at high altitude": "",
  "An air mass is a large volume of air that acquires consistent temperature and moisture properties from the surface it forms over, such as tropical ocean (warm, moist) or polar land (cold, dry).": "",
  "What is a mid-latitude cyclone?": "",
  "A large low-pressure system at temperate latitudes where warm and cold fronts interact, producing widespread weather changes": "",
  "A localized rotating windstorm that forms over continental interiors where extreme surface heating creates strong convective instability": "",
  "A large-scale tropical storm system that develops over warm ocean waters and produces sustained rotating winds exceeding 119 km/h": "",
  "A persistent high-pressure system at middle latitudes that blocks approaching fronts and maintains extended periods of dry, fair weather": "",
  "A mid-latitude cyclone is a large-scale low-pressure weather system in the 30-60 degree latitude belt where contrasting air masses interact along fronts, producing much of the changeable weather.": "",
  "What does 'wind shear' mean in the context of storms?": "",
  "The destructive erosion force that sustained winds exert on exposed structures and terrain during severe storm events": "",
  "The temporary period of calm air occurring between successive wind gusts during a thunderstorm or frontal passage": "",
  "The aggregate total wind speed measured at all atmospheric levels from the surface through the upper troposphere": "",
  "A change in wind speed or direction with altitude or horizontal distance, which can cause storm rotation": "",
  "Wind shear is the variation in wind velocity over a short distance, and strong vertical wind shear is a key ingredient for supercell development and tornado formation.": "",
  "What is a blizzard?": "",
  "A brief snow squall that produces light accumulation and moderate winds but clears within an hour as the frontal boundary quickly passes": "",
  "A severe winter storm with sustained winds of at least 56 km/h, heavy snow, and visibility below 400 meters for at least three hours": "",
  "Any snowstorm that produces measurable snow accumulation on the ground regardless of wind speed, temperature, or total duration of snowfall": "",
  "An ice storm characterized by freezing rain that coats all surfaces with a thick glaze of ice, bringing down power lines and tree branches": "",
  "A blizzard is officially defined by sustained or frequent winds of 56 km/h or more with considerable blowing snow that reduces visibility to less than 400 meters for at least three hours.": "",
  "What is a mesocyclone?": "",
  "The outer spiral bands of a hurricane": "",
  "A rotating updraft within a supercell thunderstorm that can lead to tornado formation": "",
  "A mid-latitude cyclone that has weakened": "",
  "A small-scale high-pressure system": "",
  "A mesocyclone is a region of rotation within a supercell thunderstorm, typically 3-10 km in diameter, that can tighten and descend to produce a tornado.": "",
  "What does 'tropical depression' mean?": "",
  "A formal classification on the Saffir-Simpson scale for hurricanes with sustained winds between 178 and 208 km/h at peak intensity": "",
  "A persistent region of below-average rainfall in the tropics caused by large-scale atmospheric subsidence that suppresses cloud formation": "",
  "An organized system of clouds and thunderstorms over tropical ocean with a closed circulation and sustained winds of 62 km/h or less": "",
  "An unusual period of below-normal temperatures in equatorial regions caused by shifts in ocean circulation and atmospheric cooling patterns": "",
  "A tropical depression is the first stage of tropical cyclone development, with organized thunderstorms and a closed low-level circulation but maximum sustained winds below 63 km/h.": "",
  "A weather map shows a cold front approaching your city from the west with a line of thunderstorms along it. Currently it is warm and humid with clear skies. What sequence of weather changes should you expect over the next 12 hours?": "",
  "Continuous warm weather with scattered showers": "",
  "Gradual warming followed by fog": "",
  "Increasing clouds, then a brief period of heavy rain and possibly thunderstorms, followed by a sharp temperature drop and clearing skies": "",
  "Steady light rain lasting all day with no temperature change": "",
  "Cold fronts produce a sharp weather transition: quickly building clouds, intense but brief precipitation as the steep frontal boundary passes, then rapid clearing and a noticeable temperature drop.": "",
  "A family vacationing on a Gulf Coast beach is told to evacuate as a Category 3 hurricane approaches. The main danger the emergency manager warns about is not the wind, but flooding from storm surge. Why is storm surge often deadlier than wind?": "",
  "Storm surge can push a wall of ocean water several meters deep inland, flooding vast areas rapidly and trapping people in their homes": "",
  "Wind weakens quickly once a hurricane makes landfall, so it is never dangerous": "",
  "Storm surge only occurs during Category 5 hurricanes": "",
  "Wind only affects tall buildings": "",
  "Storm surge is historically the deadliest hurricane hazard because it can push several meters of ocean water far inland in minutes, flooding everything in low-lying coastal areas.": "",
  "A storm chaser in the Great Plains observes a large supercell thunderstorm with a rotating wall cloud and hears tornado sirens. The National Weather Service confirms a tornado on the ground rated EF3. What atmospheric conditions in this region make it a prime location for violent tornadoes?": "",
  "The ocean nearby provides moisture for tornadoes": "",
  "Flat terrain prevents any wind resistance": "",
  "The collision of warm, moist air from the Gulf of Mexico with cold, dry air from Canada creates strong instability and wind shear": "",
  "Mountains funnel the wind into narrow channels": "",
  "Tornado Alley in the Great Plains is where contrasting air masses frequently collide: warm, moist Gulf air meets cold, dry Canadian air, creating strong instability and wind shear ideal for supercells.": "",
  "A weather station reports that a hurricane was Category 4 over open ocean but weakened to a tropical storm within hours of making landfall. What is the primary reason hurricanes weaken after moving over land?": "",
  "Cold rain from the hurricane cools the air and stops the storm": "",
  "Land reflects the hurricane's energy back into space": "",
  "Mountains block the wind from spinning": "",
  "The hurricane loses its warm ocean water energy source and experiences increased friction over the rougher land surface": "",
  "Hurricanes are heat engines fueled by warm ocean water; when they move over land, they lose their energy source and the increased surface friction from terrain disrupts the circulation.": "",
  "A town has experienced five days of steady, light rain from a stationary front. Local rivers are flooding even though the rain is not intense. Why can a stationary front cause worse flooding than a fast-moving cold front with heavier rain?": "",
  "The ground under stationary fronts is always more saturated to begin with": "",
  "Stationary fronts always produce more rain than cold fronts": "",
  "Stationary fronts produce warmer rain that melts snow faster": "",
  "Although the rain is lighter, a stationary front can remain over an area for days, producing much higher total rainfall accumulation": "",
  "While cold fronts produce brief heavy rain, a stationary front can stall over a region for days, allowing prolonged light-to-moderate rainfall to accumulate far more total precipitation.": "",
  "During a severe thunderstorm watch, a student notices the sky turning greenish and reports hearing a sound like a freight train. Based on these warning signs, what severe weather threat is most likely imminent?": "",
  "A heavy rain event producing flash flooding, since the green sky results from sunlight filtering through thick rain-saturated storm clouds": "",
  "An approaching blizzard with very heavy snowfall, since green skies and rumbling sounds can precede major winter storm systems in spring": "",
  "A hurricane making landfall in the region, since the greenish tint and roaring noise are features of tropical cyclone outer rain bands": "",
  "A tornado, since the green sky may indicate large hail in the storm, and the roaring sound is a classic tornado warning sign": "",
  "A green-tinted sky can indicate a severe storm with large hail, and a sound resembling a freight train is one of the most recognized warning signs of an approaching tornado.": "",
  "Two coastal cities are hit by the same Category 2 hurricane, but City A suffers catastrophic flooding while City B experiences relatively minor flooding. City A has low elevation and is at the northern side of the storm's path. What factor most likely explains the difference?": "",
  "City A has a denser arrangement of tall buildings that blocked wind flow and created pressure channels amplifying flood water through streets": "",
  "City B was located at a higher latitude where the hurricane's rotation was weaker due to reduced Coriolis effect at that distance from the tropics": "",
  "City A experienced higher storm surge because onshore winds and low elevation funneled water inland, while City B's geography reduced surge": "",
  "The hurricane lost significant wind speed and energy as it traveled between the two cities, producing substantially less rainfall when reaching City B": "",
  "Storm surge varies greatly with local geography, coastal shape, and position relative to the storm; the right side of a hurricane's path in the Northern Hemisphere typically has the worst surge.": "",
  "A meteorologist explains that a large mid-latitude cyclone forming over the Midwest involves a cold front, a warm front, and an occluded front. A student asks what happens when the occluded front forms. What is the best answer?": "",
  "The faster-moving cold front overtakes the warm front, lifting the warm air mass entirely off the ground, usually signaling the storm is weakening": "",
  "The occluded front generates severe instability that typically produces a new wave of tornadoes along the boundary between merging air masses": "",
  "Both the cold front and warm front dissolve simultaneously when their temperature contrasts equalize, causing the entire storm to end abruptly": "",
  "The warm front accelerates and overtakes the slower-moving cold front, forcing cold air aloft and significantly intensifying the storm system": "",
  "An occluded front forms when the cold front overtakes the warm front, lifting all warm air aloft, which typically marks the mature-to-dissipating stage of the mid-latitude cyclone's life cycle.": "",
  "A city experiences a record blizzard with 60 cm of snow, sustained winds of 70 km/h, and near-zero visibility. Schools and businesses close for three days. What combination of atmospheric conditions typically produces such an intense blizzard?": "",
  "A tropical storm that moved over land and turned into snow": "",
  "A powerful low-pressure system with a steep pressure gradient, abundant moisture, and cold temperatures that combine strong winds with heavy snow": "",
  "A weak warm front moving slowly through the area": "",
  "A high-pressure system blocking warm air from entering the region": "",
  "Intense blizzards require a strong low-pressure system with steep pressure gradients to drive high winds, ample moisture for heavy snow, and cold temperatures throughout the atmosphere.": "",
  "A community along a river valley experiences a flash flood after a cluster of slow-moving thunderstorms dumped 15 cm of rain in two hours. Emergency managers note that the storms kept forming over the same area. What atmospheric process causes thunderstorms to repeatedly form over the same location?": "",
  "The thunderstorms were attracted to the river": "",
  "Training echoes: outflow from one storm triggers new storms upwind in the same line, causing each storm to pass over the same area": "",
  "The jet stream held the storms in place": "",
  "Lightning from the storms caused more moisture to evaporate": "",
  "Training thunderstorms occur when storm cells repeatedly form and move over the same area like train cars on a track, causing extreme rainfall totals and dangerous flash flooding.": ""
